SET personnel transferred all remaining virgin product in the damaged tote into one (1) new 275-gallon tote, then utilized absorbents to remediate the impacted surfaces.

column168: On August 4, 2021, at approximately 11:45 AM CDT, a representative from R+L Carriers (RLC) discovered two (2) 55-gallon drums were puncutured by a forklift during transit, and released approximately five (5) gallons of UN1866 resin solution to the trailer interior. The employees at the Valspar facility took the damaged drums and removed all the liquid from the trailer. As a result, a 3' by 4' area of residual resin solution was left in trailer. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from TPM Group (TPM) to perform the necessary corrective action. TPM personnel utilized granular absorbents to remove residual free product from the impacted surface.

column168: The driver arrived at the consignee to discover that the overpack on the skid failed and most of the drums were loose in the cargo box of the truck. 3 had dark spots underneath them indicating a leak. The drums were righted and inspected by the consignee, there was no visible damage to the drums themselves. Estimated approximately 3 cups of liquid or less based on size of dark spots on the floor and that the drums still appeared to be very full. Freight is alcohol so it had mostly evaporated only leaving a mark on the wooden floor of the cargo box, but no materials/puddles.
column169: The consignee is a sister company to the shipper and the manager advised our driver that the freight should not be stacked more than 2 rows high, in this case there was a partial third row. The overpack was only shrink-wrap and the drums/wrap were not affixed to the skid in any way. I would recommend that the wrap be continued onto the base of the skid and banding be added when drums are stacked. Based on consignee's comments I would also suggest that they are not not stacked more than 2 high.

column168: On 08/11/2021 at 1506 hours EST CSXT personnel in the Spartanburg Yard (Spartanburg, SC)  discovered NATX45053, a loaded tank car of Vinyl Acetate leaking from top of the car. The car was isolated and the shipper, Celanese was notified. HEPACO, a CSXT response contractor, responded and found two of four bolts holding the liquid line to the pressure plate of the tank car less than tool tight.The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper, Celanese  Dwayne Dunn PH(979-479-6579) Dwayne.Dunn@celanese.com . HEPACO used a wrench to tighten the two loose bolts at the base of the liquid line and snooped around the valve to ensure the tank car was not leaking. The tank car is on hold pending an OTMA-3 by the shipper.

column62: Deterioration or Aging; Improper Preparation for Transportation
column168: At approximately 1935 hours on August 12, 2021 a PTRA train crew member reported product leaking from UTLX 213962 when the car was moved.  PTRA Operations manager on duty arrived on scene and noted that the product was flashing off/evaporating before it contacted the ground. He worked with the crew to slowly move the car into an isolation track for inspection and repairs. No further leakage or vapors were noticeable once the car was placed in the isolation track. On August 13, M&M Response was notified to inspect, repair and clean the car at the Manchester Yard.  Upon arrival on the scene M&M Response personnel found that two of six manway bolts were not applied, 1 of 6 bolts was hand tight and the remaining 3 of 6 bolts were tool tight.  The manway gasket was visibly pinched between the lid and manway nozzle prior to opening the lid. When M&M Response opened the manway they noted that the gasket was torn in half.  The gasket initially stuck to the manway lid but fell into the tank as the lid was opened fully.  M&M Response installed a shoulder type gasket to the manway nozzle, closed and secured the manway bolts to tool tight specs and applied a new seal.  They inspected the protective housing for any issues and found a loose, less than tool tight, liquid line plug. They secured the plug to tool tight specs and sealed the protective housing.  The exterior was then pressure washed.  The waybill indicated combustible liquid, the placards were 1993 flammable placards, after speaking with the shipper PTRA installed 1993 combustible placards on the car.  The waybill emergency contact information lists the CHEMTREC number with Tesoro Refining as the contact group. This is not a Tesoro shipment.    Chemtrec incident number is 2021081300115
column169: PTRA Safety and Env Director spoke with Safety Kleen contacts and noted the cause of the leak and the issues with the waybill/placard information.  They are looking into the issues and taking steps to eliminate future occurrences.

column42: PETROLEUM DISTILLATES, N.O.S. OR PETROLEUM PRODUCTS, N.O.S.
column168: On 8-6-2021 at 0550 personnel in the CSXT Siebert Yard discovered UTLX669593, a loaded  tank car of Petroleum Distillates, N.O.S. leaking from manway. The car was isolated and  Chemtrec was notified and to notify the shipper Resinall Corporation (CHEMTREC Report  #2021080600061). SPSI, a CSXT response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and  found that product has ran down the side of the car and that vapors were present around  the tank car.  The issue identified and corrective actions were taken to stop the release.  Contractor personnel found that 6 of 8 manway swing bolts were less than tool tight.   Contractor opened manway to inspect the gasket.  Gasket was found to satisfactory  condition.  Manway was closed and manway swing bolts were properly tool tightened.  The leak was secured and the car released for transport. This incident did not require a  special switching move.
column169: (NAR code:200 5  What Failed: Manway, Hinged & Bolted  Where Failed: Connection between manway nozzle and manway cover  Why Failed: Bolts/nuts - less than tool tight)

column168: On August 16, 2021, personnel at the R+L Carriers (RLC) terminal located at the above-referenced address observed a cargo leak in trailer on the dock located at dock door 11. Upon further inspection, one (1) 330-gallon steel tote of UN1915 cyclohexanone was leaking from a weld at the outlet and released less than one gallon of product to the concrete dock floor. RLC retained Cura Emergency Services, LC (CES), who dispatched a crew from Environmental Works (EW) to perform the necessary corrective action. EW personnel determined the weld could not be repaired and transferred all remaining virgin product into six (6) 55-gallon drums for continued transport. Absorbents were utilized to remediate the impacted surface.

On 08/08/21at 0909hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Colum bus OH terminal discovered MSKU759978, a loaded container of 78dr UN1987, Alcohols NOS (ethanol, isopropanol quaternary ammonium compounds), 3, III, 5.2, in 55gallon steel drums, released estimate of 1gal white substance drips onto asphalt pavement. The container was isolated and Ohio Environmental Protection Agency was notified, report#2108EPA000. The shipper, MAERSK Inc, representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, case#281350. CSXT emergency response contractor, HEPACO Environmental, was dispatched to the scene and found one 55gallon steel drum released 1gal of product due to being rusted/corroded on bottom rim.  The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. Contractor personnel secured the release by transfer of product into overpack, deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site. The original freight container with proper load/block/brace was released to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switching move. This incident did not require a Form 7.1.

THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF LESS THAN 2" OF FOAM PEANUTS AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX, RATED AT A 275 LBS PER SQ INCH BURSTING TEST.

column168: On 08/25/2021, at 1357, personnel from CSX discovered LTCX196 on the CSX mainline in Danville IN, a loaded tank car of Argon, Refrigerated Liquid, leaking from the valve containment cabinet. The car was isolated and Linde Inc., NRC, and IDEM were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0825-00294). Response Management Services, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found the main liquid valve left open and the liquid fill hose drain left open. The issue was identified and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper Michael Bolton, 716-435-1606. Contractor personnel closed both the liquid and liquid fill hose drain valves. The leak was secured and the car was released for transport. This incident did not require a special switching move. No 7.1 is required  Cause Code: 117 NARRI: 5

DMP RECEIVED A RADIO CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE ON A BULK CART AT DOOR 77. UPON ARRIVAL, THE RESPONDER FOUND THAT A WAREHOUSE WORKER MOVED THE PACKAGE AND PLACED IT ON THE GROUND. TOLUENE WAS LEAKING ONTO THE FLOOR AND HAD ALREADY LEAKED ON THE BULK CART. IT APPEARS THAT THE PACKAGE WAS THROWN ONTO THE BULK CART CAUSING ONE OF THE INNER BOTTLES TO SHATTER COMPLETELY, MELTING THE STYROFOAM HOLDING CONTAINER, SOAKING THE PACKAGE, AND LEAKING ONTO THE BULK CART AND THE FLOOR. RESPONDER IMMEDIATELY IDENTIFIED THE CONTENTS AS A FLAMMABLE LIQUID PER MARKINGS ON PACKAGE. FOLLOWED DECISION TREE AND RESPONSE SHEETS FOR CLEANUP AND DISPOSAL. RESPONDER NOTIFIED RMP OF SPILL AND THAT PACKAGE WAS MOVED PRIOR TO RESPONDER ARRIVING ON THE SCENE OF THE INCIDENT.
NO DESCRIPTION PROVIDED

column168: On August 3, 2021 at 1255 ET, XPO Logistics terminal LTU contacted ERTS regarding the release of UN2922 Glycidyl Methacrylate. It was reported that a 55 gallon steel drum was damaged and released an unknown amount of material inside the trailer. ERTS has dispatched ERS of OK to conduct the cleanup.  At 1600 EST, ERS personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 1 gallon of product released to a 3' x 3' area of the trailer floor with 1 cup of material impacting the asphalt lot below. Absorbents were worked into the impacted areas and collected into a 55 gallon metal drum. The damaged drum was overpacked into an 85 gallon metal drum. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: On 08/26/2021, at 0957 hours, FRA 2inspecter Steven Myers in the CSXT Kenmore Yard discovered GATX54531 a loaded tank car of Methyl Methacrylate, leaking from the liquid lime valve equator handle seal area. The car was isolated and the shipper, National Response Center, and New York State Department of Environmental Conservation were notified.  (CHEMTREC Report #2021-0826-00158).Enviroserve, a CSXT emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the scene and found Methyl Methacrylate dripping from liquid line actuator handle seal. Upon further inspection, all other service equipment was properly secured. Enviroserve personnel tightened two (2) loose tensioning screws on the liquid line stem packing gland utilizing hand tools securing the leak. This incident did not require a special switching move. 7.1 is not required?  Cause Code: 296  NARRI: 112
column169: NAR cause code:296What Failed: Liquid Line / Liquid Valve  Where Failed: Valve stem  Why Failed: Loose packing retainer

On August 3, 2021 at 0027 ET XPO Logistics XCW notified ERTS of a 2-gallon release of Dynachlor from a 55-gallon poly drum due to a faulty lid, impacting the trailer floor. She is confident that she can resecure the lid and ship the product on. ERTS reviewed the SDS with the caller and the terminal feels comfortable cleaning the release with PPE available on site. Oil Dri will be utilized to collect the spilled material. The waste and cleanup debris will be placed into a 10-gallon poly waste container.

US Ecology cargo tanker 50020 was loaded with 3,600 gallons of sulfuric acid pickle sludge at the customer site - Plymouth tube (Winamac, IN). The US Ecology operator heard "a noise" that indicated something was not right with the tanker as he was preparing to leave the Plymouth Tube site. He pulled tanker 50020 over to a secure area to inspect it and found the knife valve for loading and un-loading had begun to leak.   Tanker 50020 had recently completed its annual inspections and repairs were made to the knife valve at local vendor, United Tank Parts Incorporated, 19300 Meginnity Street, Melvindale, MI 48122 (CT Registry #2732).   The operator used spill mats and buckets under the leaking valve. Site employees at the Plymouth Tube quickly built a containment berm while US Ecology operators that were on site offloaded tanker 50020 onto another tanker. Through the event, approximately 40 gallons released to the ground.
column169: During a thorough investigation between United Tank Parts Incorporated and US Ecology, it had been discovered that United Tank Parts had installed the wrong, incompatible valve on to US Ecology cargo tanker 50020. Custom Tank acknowledged their error and  is currently installing the proper, compatible valve and has also agreed to pay for the spill clean-up and disposal of the waste material.

column168: On August 11, 2021, at 10:15 am, an FRA inspector was conducting compliance inspections in Marinette, Wisconsin at the interchange with the Escanaba & Lake Superior Railroad, discovering GATX 8247 hissing and venting from the manway. The FRA Inspector reported the release to CN's local Dangerous Goods Officer. CN initiated emergency response protocols and CN's Dangerous Goods Officer responded to the incident. Upon arrival, CN Dangerous Goods Officer conducted an assessment of GATX 8247 noting the shipper's security seal intact. CN Dangerous Goods Officer inspected the manway, discovering manway cover swing bolts less than tool tight. The manway cover was opened and the gasket was inspected for damage. The manway gasket was deteriorated during visual inspection. The lid gasket groove was cleaned and a new manway gasket was installed. The manway was properly secured and a new security seal applied.

column168: On 08/026/21 at 0604hrs personnel with CSX Intermodal Bedford Park FL Terminal discovered EXFU145260, a loaded 40ft portable tank of UN1993, Flammable Liquids Nos (octane), 3, III, leaked less than 10gals of liquid from the top vacuum relief valve with minimal amount onto asphalt pavement. The release was due to turnover when stuck by outside party driver. The ILL EMA was notified, report# H-2021-0784.   The shipper, Quality Carriers Inc, representative was notified by CSXI Customer Service, Case 00293439. CSXT emergency response contractor, ENVIROSERVE, was dispatched to the scene and found the top vacuum relief valve released less than 10gallons of product due to tank being on its side. The tank was uprighted, release stopped, and corrective actions were communicated to the shipper. The Response Contractor personnel secured deconned spilled areas, and cleaned up the release site. The original 40ft tank with secured product was released to the shipper.  This incident did not require a special switching move. This incident did not require a Form 7.1

column168: On August 9, 2021, at 0830 hours, Yardmaster at the Conrail Stoney Creek Yard, Chester, Pennsylvania  reported that a hissing sound was heard from atop TILX 304209, a residue last contained tank car of  UN1077, PROPYLENE. The tank car was isolated and the employees were told to stay away from the  immediate area. The shipper, Braskem, was notified via phone directly. Marion Environmental, a Conrail emergency response contractor, was dispatched to the Stoney Creek Yard as well as Joe Caccamo,  Conrail Manager of Hazardous Material. Upon inspection it was found that the vapor line was partially  open and the secondary securement plug was less than tool tight.. The shipper representative, Bill Mercer,  215-360-7586 was notified of the situation found. FRA Hazardous Material Inspector Marc Dougherty was  informed of the NAR and remedy and approved the placement back into transportation of TILX 304209.   NARRI: 5x(4+5+0)x(2+0) = 90 Cause code:136

column168: FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE AND EMITTING A STRONG, PUNGENT ODOR BY A SORTER IN SORT AISLE-E. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF THE CONVEYOR BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR, DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN 4 MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON), THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 2 PLASTIC 5-LITER JUGS WAS LOOSE BY 1/4 ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 8 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THE INNER PACKING MATERIAL CONSISTED OF A DOUBLE CORRUGATED CARTON CONFIGURATION AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A SINGLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX RATED AT 44 LBS/IN EDGE CRUSH TEST (ECT).

column42: HYDROGEN PEROXIDE AND PEROXYACETIC ACID MIXTURES, STABILIZED WITH ACIDS, WATER, AND NOT MORE THAN 5 PERCENT PEROXYACETIC ACID
column168: RECEIVE A CALL FOR A LEAKING PACKAGE A LOAD AREA. ARRIVED WITH PROPER PPE, FOUND A LEAKING PACKAGE ON THE FLOOR. BROUGHT BACK TO DMP AREA FOR FURTHER PROCESSING

PACKAGE WAS BROUGHT TO THE DMP BY THE RESPONDER FROM DOOR 16 ON THE UNLOAD AROUND 1:30 AM. IN THE DMP THE PACKAGE WAS OPENED AND FOUND TO CONTAIN TWO, 2.5 GALLON, PLASTIC BOTTLES OF CONVOCLEAN FORTE, AN ALKALINE CLEANER BEING SHIPPED AS A CORROSIVE HAZ-MAT, (UN1814 POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE SOLUTION, 8, II). THE CAPS ON BOTH 2.5 GALLON BOTTLES WHERE LOOSE WHICH ALLOWED A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE CORROSIVE LIQUID TO ESCAPE FROM BOTH BOTTLES, AND STAIN THE OUTSIDE CARTON. ALL PRODUCT WAS PROCESSED THROUGH THE DMP ACCORDING TO REGULATIONS.
WEARING PROPER PPE RESPONDER ROZELLE PICKED UP PACKAGE AND RETURNED TO DMP FOR FURTHER PROCESSING.
RESPONDER RESPONDED TO AREA OF SPILL, CONTAINED - SPILL TRAY, RETURNED TO THE DMP FOR PROCESSING.

FULLY LABELED HAZ-MAT SHIPMENT WAS VISUALLY DISCOVERED WET IN APPEARANCE BY THE HVD PICK-OFF ON THE PD-4. WITHOUT TOUCHING THE PKG HE TURNED OFF THE BELT, EVACUATED THE AREA AND NOTIFIED HIS IMMEDIATE SUPERVISOR. DMP WAS CONTACTED AND WITHIN A FEW MINUTES A RESPONDER ARRIVED, DONNING THE PROPER PPE. AFTER FOLLOWING THE DECISION TREE   APPROPRIATE RESPONSE SHEET THE DAMAGE WAS CONTAINED (NO SPILLAGE OUTSIDE OF CARTON, THEN TRANSPORTED TO THE DMP PROCESSING AREA. CLOSER INSPECTION REVEALED THAT THE CAP ON 1 OF 4 PLASTIC 1-GAL JUGS WAS LOOSE BY A FULL ROTATION, CAUSING APPROX. 8 OZ OF THE LIQUID TO LEAK THROUGH THE BREACH AND INTO THE CARTON. THERE WAS NO INTERNAL PACKING MATERIAL AND THE OUTER CARTON WAS A DOUBLEWALL FIBERBOARD BOX.

column168: UNIT 1011/265 (THE VEHICLE) WAS TRAVELING EAST ON US 70. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE TRAVELED OFF THE ROADWAY TO THE RIGHT AND OVERCORRECTED CAUSING THE VEHICLE TO OVERTURN. AFTER OVERTURNING THE VEHICLE BECAME SEPARATED FROM IT'S TRAILER AND BOTH THE BOBTAIL AND TRAILER CAME TO REST OFF THE RIGHT SHOULDER. THE RELEASED GASOLINE WAS VACUUMED AND ABSORBANTS WERE APPLIED. ESTIMATED DURATION OF THE RELEASE WAS 4-5 HRS. THE MAJOR DAMAGE TO THE TRAILER WAS THE RIPPED SHELL (TOP AT VAPOR RAIL) AND THE BUSTED WELDS BETWEEN THE BULKHEADS. THE DRIVER OF THE VEHICLE WAS EJECTED AND PRONOUNCED DECEASED AS A RESULT OF HIS INJURIES. THE DRIVER WAS NOT WEARING SEATBELT AT THE TIME OF THE CRASH.
column169: COMPANY STANDARD OPERATING PROCEDURES AND TRAINING STANDARDS REQUIRE WEARING OF SEATBELTS ANYTIME A VEHICLE IS IN OPERATION. IT IS ALSO THE LAW. EVERY DRIVER IS AWARE OF THIS REQUIREMENT. IN ORDER TO MONITOR THE USE OF SEATBELTS DURING THE WORK SHIFT, IT MAY BE NECESSARY TO ADD AN INWARD FACING CAMERA IN THE TRUCK CABS. THE DRIVER WAS COMPLIANT ON HOS, AND THE DOT INSPECTION OF THE EQUIPMENT CONFIRMED THERE WAS NO MECHANICAL OR MAINTENANCE ISSUES WITH THE EQUIPMENT AT THE TIME OF THE CRASH.

column168: On August 10, 2021 at 0503 ET XPO Logistics XCO notified ERTS of a cargo release at XCO. It was reported that 5 gallons of Ferric Chloride, Solution released from a tote due to damage by freight. ERTS reviewed the SDS with XPO, terminal determined that a contractor would need to conduct the cleanup. EnviroServe arrived onsite at 0600 ET and confirmed approximately five (5)-gallons of product released affecting an 8’ x 15’ area of the trailer floor and 1’ x 2’ of the concrete floor below. Contractors transferred all salvageable material into a new 330-gallons poly tote and collected and containerized the damaged cut-up tote and all clean-up debris into two (2) 55-gallons poly drums. All waste was staged onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

column168: Driver was hooked up to a drop tank dropping product, when he proceeded to hook up another compartment and tank to start dropping UNL. The driver realized that his hose was not long enough and that he would need to adjust the trailer so the drop tank. The driver got into the truck and began to back the truck to up closer to the tank. When the hose that was already hooked and had product flowing through it, got stretched to the point that it separated causing a 5 1/2 gallon spill of UNL. column168: Upon completion of loading a cargo tank motor vehicle, driver was leaving the loading facility and pulled out onto the highway. The local fire department along with emergency response personnel were dispatched to the scene to protect the scene as well as provide the necessary clean up services. The emergency response crew cleaned up the spill and properly disposed of the small amount of waste.

On 8-31-2021, the WLE Brewster Yard Switch Crew was walking their cut of cars when they noticed tank car GATX 5003 having an odor coming from it.  They called the local trainmaster, who when investigating, noticed that the car was hissing from the top of the car as well as having an odor.  He called the Brewster Yardmaster who then called myself, John Vergis, WLE Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer.  I came out to look at the car and found that both the liquid valves were leaking through the valve plugs.  I checked to see if the valve handles were loose and they were.  I tightened the handles on both valves and the leaks stopped.  I checked the valve plugs and both were less than hand tight.  I installed thread tape on the plugs and reinstalled them.  I also checked the plug on the vapor valve and it was loose.  I tightened it also but it was not leaking.  I removed old seal #6894136 from the Protective housing cover and installed new seal 971742.  The car was then OK for service.  NARRI: 5(4+5+0)x(2+0)=90
column169: Better procedures need followed for car securement.

column168: On 8-28-2021 at 2030 hrs., the WLE Mingo Yard switch crew notice tank car NATX 310044 having an odor coming from it and also wetness around the manway lid on top of the car.  They called the Mingo Yard Master who then contacted myself, John Vergis Hazardous Materials/Environmental Officer for the WLE.  I called Specialized Professional Services out of Washington, PA to look at the car.  When they arrived and investigated, the noticed that the manway lid was leaking from the handle area.  They opened the lid to find that the gasket was in good order.  What they found was, according to marks on the gasket, that the lid was not lined up properly to the manway nozzle.  This misallignment caused the metal surface of the manway nozzle to seal against the metal portion of the manway lid, not the gasket portion of the lid.  This caused the lid to not seal properly causing a slight liquid spillage as the car moved and also a vapor dispersion.  They reset the lid to the nozzle and tightened the lid appropriately.  The car was then returned to service.  NARRI: 5(5+3+0)x(2+0)=80
column169: More attention needs paid to the lid when closing it.

SequenceEvent: Unload Manager notified QA of a hazmat damage in the unload, and manager placed package on a spill tray at unload bay door 11. QA retrieved the damaged hazmat using gloves, absorbent pads, and a plastic bag lined bin and transported it over to the QA Cage with a push cart. DescribePack: At first glance it was clear to see that there was a wet spot along the edge of the box and on the top of one side. After opening it up with a box cutter it appeared the leak was from the bottle of Concentrated Liquid Dishmachine Detergent and there were droplets surrounding where the cap was at. Most of the liquid is still in the bottle and there wasn't any damage along the body of the bottle either. Nor, was their evidence of a leak anywhere else on the box. DurationRel: 1 and MitigateEffect: As soon as the unload manager notified QA about the hazmat the package was immediately placed on a spill tray. I asked if it had spilled onto the floor and it had not. Since it is corrosive I put absorbent pads in the bin and then lined it with a thick plastic bag, and with gloved hands I put the package into the bin. From there we transported it to the QA cage where I inspected it further for any cracks, punctures, or damage of any kind while keeping the contents in the lined bin.

column168: At 0526 EST, XPO Logistics notified ERTS that 2 cups of UN3262 JEM Extreme Heat FA Powder Drain and Sewer Opener released from a 5 gallon poly drum. The weight of the containers broke the pallet and cracked the pail. ERTS was unable to locate the SDS for the product therefore a contractor was dispatched to clean the release. At 1110 EST, First Call personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 5 cups of product released to a 1' x 1' area of the trailer floor. The material was collected and containerized along with the damaged pail into a 55 gallon poly drum. The waste was left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

On August 23, 2021 at 2155 EST, XPO Logistics Terminal XER reported trailer 463-2307 arrived with a damaged 55 gallon poly drum containing UN1789 Hydrochloric Acid Solution. The drum fell in transit due to improper loading. Terminal personnel requested contactor response. ERTS dispatched Environmental Remediation & Recovery (ERR) to conduct cleanup. On August 24, 2021, at 0030 EST, ERR personnel arrived onsite and confirmed 55 gallons released, and the immediately began containing the release with hydrated lime and absorbents. ERR reported the release from the trailer was 2' x 30', then trailed to the east in a 2' x 80' trail leading to a 4' pooled area. At  EST, ERR stopped working for the night to return at 0830 EST to cut up the impacted pallet and finish cleaning the impacted area. The nose of the trailer had product slowly dripping from the product seeping under the floor. The crew placed buckets to catch the release, all impacted areas were contained, and all free product was neutralized with hydrated lime. At 0910 EST, ERR personnel returned to the site and collected all impacted absorbents/lime acid mixture into (2) 55 gallon poly drums. The damaged drum containing the product was transferred into a new 55 gallon poly drum. The trailer was neutralized and they cleaned the trailer and outside the trailer with Hydrated Lime. They also raised & lowered the trailer to ensure no more product would leak out. ERR advised there is a small amount of staining from neutralizer but this came back as 6.5 pH with strips. Crew cut up the damaged drum and pallet and containerized this into a 55 gallon poly drum. A total of (4) 55 gallon drums were left onsite for terminal personnel to manage.

One 5 gallon poly pail of UN3109 was crushed during loading operations. A forklift ran over the pail when it fell off a pallet, causing the entire contents to spill. Hazmat contractors were dispatched for cleanup and containment.

column168: On 2021/08/30 CN mechanical department employee noted odor coming from tank cars on the M34041-29 lines 39-43, 60-70 and lines 172-155 during an inspection at the CN Superior Yard, Superior, WI. Unable to pinpoint the exact car(s) it was coming from. The cars were spotted on LZ08 in Superior yard. All appropriate departments notified, tank cars isolated. CN's response team responded noting TCIX 5124 (L/UN2448/Sulphur, Molten/Class 4.1/PG III) was leaking, all closures closed and seals intact. The odor appeared to be coming from the BOV. Air monitoring confirmed that the BOV was leaking. All swing bolts on the manway were checked for tightness as well as the BOV and found to be tool tight. The tank car is being held for trans load.

column168: During off loading of the plane there was evidence of a leak on several packages. When tested with pH paper it was between an 11-12 pH. Upon inspection of the shipments in the ABK area of the plane, the leaking package was found. It was a FedEx Pak and inside the Pak was a 1 Litre plastic bottle of a product manufactured by Advanced Nutrients called PH-UP. I obtained the manufacturer's Safety Data Sheet (SDS) on line and Section 14 identifies/classifies this product as UN 1814, Potassium Hydroxide, Class 8 corrosive material, Packing Group II. There was also a GHS label on the inner product with the corrosive pictogram. As the shipper had not offered the shipment with any DG markings, DG labels, nor a shipper's declaration and the automation label did not indicate a DG handling code it is undeclared or hidden DG. The shipment was held pending FAA notification(email, photos and the manufacturer's SDS sent via email) and their release of the shipment.

column168: On 8/9/2021 at 9:00 PM, Kansas City Southern Railway(KCS) personnel working in the KCS Shreveport, LA rail yard notified KCS Environmental& Hazmat that loaded tank car NATX 72643(UN3082/OTHER REGULATED SUBSTANCE S, LIQUID, N.O.S./9/PG 111) was Ieaklng from the top of the car. A railroad qualified response contractor was moblllzed to investigate and mitlgate the leak. Upon initial Inspection, the responders discovered NATX 72643 had 5 manway swing bolts less than tool tight& no manway nozzle gasket Installed. Responders Installed a new 20" Viton manway nozzle gasket, tightened manway swing bolts tool tight, and Installed a new security seal on manway& protective housing. Once the other closures were confirmed tool tight, the car was released back into transportation. Estimated 5 gallon product release. File Note: Item 19-the quantity released was estimated based on the best information available at the time of filing. This shipment was offered as a'bulk' shipment, aka one car load, therefore the exact amount offered in this package Is not known to the carrier. This carrier does not have access to mass balance data which can exactly quantify this value.
column169: The Kansas City Southern Railway(KCSR) notified shipper of this release. Non Accidental Releases(NAR) can be devastating on several different levels. They can cause personal injury, environmental damage, disrupt rail yards, adJacent facilities and communities, and snarl train operations for hundreds of miles and both directions. NARs are troublesome to all because they are, by and large, preventable. For non accident releases(a.k.a. package closure issues such as this), the shipper is requested to conduct a root-cause Investigation to determine the cause(s) of release and to then facilitate corrective action to prevent recurrence. It Is requested that the shipper share their findings with KCS.(Please direct your root cause Investigation results and corrective actions to Steve McNealy, KCS Railway, P.O. Box 219335, Kansas City, MO 64121. The shipper can reference http://nar.aar.com for help understanding and preventing NARs. (NAR: 200,207)

A fiberboard box was laentlr lea containing undeclared dangerous goods at the Fedex Express origin station in Des Moines, IA. The package was shipped by National Carwash Solutiohs from Grimes, IA. Operations staff noted a small GHS marking indicating skin corrosion on the outer box, but there were no other markings or labels indicating Dangerous Goods on the box, and no Shippers Declaration for Dangerous Goods was offered with the shipment. Two plastic bottles were visible through handle cutout in the outer packaging, and a product label on the outside of the box near the GHS marking indicated the shipment contained Prep Pro 1 Low pH Presoak manufactured by National Carwash Solutions. The SDS document associated with the·product indicates it is classified as UN1760, Corrosive Liquid, N.O. S., packing group III. The destination station was directed by FedEx Dangerous Goods Administration to hold the shipment pending further disposition instruction.

column168: On 8/17/21 at 1000 ET, ESTES expereinced a two gallon release of UN1789, Hydrochloric Acid, 8, PGII"Muriatic Acid" from two(1) gallon poly jugs that were damaged in transit due to improper loading. Allied International Emergency was dispatched to the site. Upon the contractor's arrival, an 8' by 4' area of the concrete dock was confirmed impacted by two gallons of product. Granular absorbents were applied to the dock floor to solidify the free- standing Iiquids. The impacted solids were then collected and containerized. The empty, damaged containers as well as other damaged containers that had not been released but had reacted with the humidity in the air were also containerized. All waste generated, three(3) 55- gallon poly drums and one(1) 95- gallon poly drum were all staged onsite at the terminal.

column168: ON AUGUST 11, 2021, DRIVER LOADED THE TRUCK AT THE WEST BERLIN BULK PLANT WITH 2800 GALLONS OF OFF-ROAD DIESEL. PROCEEDED SOUTH ON VT RTE 12 AND VT RTE 12A FOR DELIVERIES ON THE ROXBURY AREA. APPROXIMATELY 1 MILE SOUTH OF THE VT STATE ROXBURY FISH HATCHERY, NEAR THE PAVED PULL OFF ON THE EAST SIDE OF THE ROAD, THE DRIVER DRIFTED TO THE RIGHT EDGE OF THE ROAD, ATTEMPTED TO CORRECT THE VEHICLE TURNING SHARPLY LEFT, THE LIQUID LOAD IN THE TANK SHIFTED AND THE TRUCK ROLLED OVER. DUE TO THE DEFORMATION OF THE CARGO TANK IN THE ROLLOVER, THE TOP COVERS/DOME COVER LEAKED PRODUCT. EMERGENCY SERVICES WERE CALLED, A SPILL RESPONSE COMPANY WAS CALLED. EFFORTS WERE MADE TO MINIMIZE THE LEAKAGE THROUGH THE TOP COVERS UNTIL EMERGENCY SERVICES ARRIVED. ADDITIONAL COMPANY TRUCK WAS DISPATCHED TO THE SCENE TO PUMP OFF THE LOAD OF THE OVERTURNED TRUCK.
column169: WE CONDUCTED A SAFETY MEETING THE FOLLOWING DAY WITH ALL COMPANY EMPLOYEES REVIEWING THE ACCIDENT, HOW IT OCCURRED, AND WHAT VIOLATIONS WERE DISCOVERED. IN ADDITION, WE CONDUCTED A MORE IN-DEPTH SAFETY MEETING WITH ALL COMPANY EMPLOYEES THAT COVERED EMERGENCY RESPONSE PROCEDURES, PROPER PLACARDING, REVIEWED THE EMERGENCY RESPOSNE GUIDEBOOK, IMPLEMENTED AND REVIEWED PROPER SHIPPING PAPER PROCEDURES AND FORM, SAFE DRIVING, DISTRACTED DRIVING, ETC.  WE ALSO MET WITH THE DRIVER OF THE TRUCK TO DISCUSS SAFE DRIVING, DISTRACTED DRIVING, AND CONSEQUENCES FOR ANY FUTURE USE OF HANDHELD ELECTRONIC DEVICES WHILE OPERATING A CMV. WHILE WE DID NOT FIND EVIDENCE OF THE DRIVER WAS USING THEIR HANDHELD ELECTRONIC DEVICE (NO SERVICE IN THE ACCIDENT AREA), WE WANTED TO MAKE SURE WE WERE VERY CLEAR ON THIS POINT.

column168: Friday, August 20, 2021@ 1042 Mr. Mousa Alshair of Kiswani National Inc(KNI) called Environmental Management, Inc.(EMI) and spoke to Mr. Matt Girard. Mr. Alshair stated that a trailer double stacked with 55 gallon drums of a flammable liquid(Dimethyl Carbonate) has a leak. He requested a team to inspect the leaking trailer and clean up any release. Mr. Girard contacted Young's Environmental Cleanup, Inc(YECI) in Grand Rapids, MI and requested a team to respond to the above incident. Mr. Girard stated that the team will need to unload the ftammable drums from the trailer and find the Ieaking drum. The team arrived onsite 1130 and began inspecting the trailer. The team layed out plastic to stage the pallets of drums for inspection. The team began removing the double stacked pallets from the trailer. The team found one drum slowly leaking from its bottom ring/chime. There was a slight dent in the area but no visual hole. The team overpacked the drum. The team inspected the remaining drums as well. There was no release to clean up because the released material had evaporated. The team estimated less than 5 gallons was released. The oven)acked drum was left onsite. The team did not generate any waste. No further action is required.
column169: Inspect drums during loading and unloading to ensure the drums are secure and not touching other drums.
